@wojtek0806 @zancas I am of the opinion that we should be future-proofing ourselves and our customers against lack of development; as F5 is notorious for this. If we lock in to specific versions then we cannot even test new versions until we adapt the code.

imho this is no different from every other open source project on earth. The core developers have a specific agenda and they work on that, but that does not preclude someone from using the software beyond what it is documented to support.

If they choose to do that, then they are on their own. Just to reinforce that point, call it out specifically on the front-page of the readme that, as far as we know, this only works on these enumerated platforms that we have tested.

@graingert Who would try to install the `.post1` version? It's identical to the `2.4.1` version - the only reason there's a `post1` version at all is because I didn't realize that you can't delete and re-release source distributions with the same numeric version (the code is identical, but the original source distributions didn't include the test suite because of a bug in I think setuptools).

The only reason I didn't change the version string in the code was because I was under the impression that the `postN` notation was for problems with the build, and that the true "version number" for 2.4.1 and 2.4.1.post1 would be the same.

